Prove that matrix equation $AX-XA=I$ doesn't have a solution for any $A\in M_n(\mathbb{R})$ If $n=2,$ $$A=
        \begin{bmatrix}
        x & y \\
        u & v  \\
        \end{bmatrix}
$$ $$X=
        \begin{bmatrix}
        \alpha \\
        \beta \\
        \end{bmatrix}
$$ $\Rightarrow AX-XA=O\neq I$ What is the more strict proof?

I have to find sum (or the least upper bound) of infinite series (exact expression not decimal number) of series $\begin{equation}
\sum_{k=1}^{+\infty}\frac{k!(1+k)^k}{(k^2)!}
\end{equation}$. I am clueless, thank you for any help.
